–Female":"1015–Overleden","1080–1138":"1080–1138","1014–1082":"1014–1082","1080":"1080","1138":"1138","1015":"1015","1014":"1014","after 1082":"na 1082","1066":"1066","1082":"1082","Manche, Normandy, France":"Manche, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1014–after 1082":"1014–after 1082","1015–Female":"1015–Deceased","1080–1138":"1080–1138","1014–1082":"1014–1082","1080":"1080","1138":"1138","1015":"1015","1014":"1014","after 1082":"after 1082","1066":"1066","1082":"1082","Manche, Normandy, France":"Manche, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Bertrand","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval French variant of   Bertram  , imported to Britain by the Normans. In modern times it has been made famous by the English philosopher  Bertrand Russell  (  1872–1970 ), but is only in occasional use."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert I Bertrand de Bricquebec was born in 1014, in Manche, Normandy, France. He had at least 1 son with Suzanne de Bertrand. He registered for military service in 1066. He died after 1082, in his hometown."},"et":{"1014–after 1082":"1014–pärast 1082","1015–Female":"1015–Surnud","1080–1138":"1080–1138","1014–1082":"1014–1082","1080":"1080","1138":"1138","1015":"1015","1014":"1014","after 1082":"pärast 1082","1066":"1066","1082":"1082","Manche, Normandy, France":"Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1014–after 1082":"1014–1082 jälkeen","1015–Female":"1015–Kuollut","1080–1138":"1080–1138","1014–1082":"1014–1082","1080":"1080","1138":"1138","1015":"1015","1014":"1014","after 1082":"1082 jälkeen","1066":"1066","1082":"1082","Manche, Normandy, France":"Manche, Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1014–after 1082":"1014–après 1082","1015–Female":"1015–Décédée","1080–1138":"1080–1138","1014–1082":"1014–1082","1080":"1080","1138":"1138","1015":"1015","1014":"1014","after 1082":"après 1082","1066":"1066","1082":"1082","Manche, Normandy, France":"Manche, Normandie, France","lifeSummary":"Robert I Bertrand de Bricquebec est né en 1014, à Manche, Normandie, France. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Suzanne de Bertrand. Il s'est inscrite au service militaire en 1066. Il est décédé après 1082, dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1014–after 1082":"1014–nach 1082","1015–Female":"1015–Versto